{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493365"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1302"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1302"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.45,0.17,0.04,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1302"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70873"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1800"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"7864"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28477"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man undergoes an oesophagectomy for locally-advanced oesophageal adenocarcinoma. The procedure is uneventful and a chest drain is inserted as standard practice. He makes a steady post-operative recovery, however, four days after the procedure the following contents are noted in the drainage bag (Image 1). He reports some increasing difficulty with breathing in the last day or so.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well, with a blood pressure of 123/89, pulse 84/min, temperature 37.2C, respiratory rate 21/min and SpO2 94% on 2L/min of oxygen. He has good chest expansion, with normal breath sounds in all areas apart from the right base, where there is some dullness to percussion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the drain contents?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Standard drainage from the chest","Thoracic duct injury","Anastomotic leak","Acute pulmonary oedema","Empyema"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this is a chylothorax secondary to \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Ethoracic duct injury\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E. The thoracic duct is the largest lymphatic duct in the body, draining lymph from the entire body excluding the right hemithorax, right head and neck and right upper limb. Several aetiologies are possible for thoracic duct injury, including traumatic causes, iatrogenic causes (e.g., surgery to oesophagus, aorta, pleura, lung) malignancies (e.g., lymphoma, mediastinal tumours, primary lung cancers) and various other causes (e.g., liver cirrhosis, thoracic aortic aneurysm, amyloidosis, sarcoidosis). Patients most commonly develop pleural effusions involving the right hemithorax. However, as this patient has recently had an oesophagectomy, and the thoracic duct is closely associated with the oesophagus, it is likely that this structure has been inadvertently damaged in the course of surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStandard chest drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is more likely to be serosanguinous in nature, which appears as yellowish discharge with small amounts of blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eanastamotic leak\u003C/strong\u003E is a relatively common cause of morbidity following oesophageal surgery. An anastomotic leak would be more likely to present with fever, tachycardia, increased chest drain output, or recurrent coughing when swallowing. This is unlikely to be the cause in this patient, given both the lack of significant examination findings, and appearance of the drainage fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pulmonary oedema \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be more likely to present in an individual with significant cardiac history (i.e., CCF, ischaemic heart disease, vascular risk factors such as diabetes mellitus and hypertension), and would also be more likely to have frothy pink-red colour drainage fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eempyema\u003C/strong\u003E may present with purulent drainage fluid from within the pleural space, however would be more likely in a patient presenting with significant respiratory symptoms (e.g., acute-onset cough productive of purulent sputum, dyspnoea).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thoracic duct injury is a rare complication of head and neck surgery","Chylothoraces most commonly result from thoracic duct injury, and often present as milky-white chest drainage fluid"],"references":["Bojanapu S, Khan YS. Thoracic Duct Leak. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560549/","Polistena A, Vannucci J, Monacelli M, Lucchini R, Sanguinetti A, Avenia S, Santoprete S, Triola R, Cirocchi R, Puma F, Avenia N. Thoracic duct lesions in thyroid surgery: An update on diagnosis, treatment and prevention based on a cohort study. Int J Surg. 2016 Apr;28 Suppl 1:S33-7. doi: 10.1016/j.ijsu.2015.05.058. Epub 2015 Dec 18. PMID: 26708844. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26708844/","Johnson OW, Chick JF, Chauhan NR, Fairchild AH, Fan CM, Stecker MS, Killoran TP, Suzuki-Han A. The thoracic duct: clinical importance, anatomic variation, imaging, and embolization. Eur Radiol. 2016 Aug;26(8):2482-93. doi: 10.1007/s00330-015-4112-6. Epub 2015 Dec 1. PMID: 26628065. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26628065/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70873"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1302"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20060"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20060"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/978154de-383c-49c9-a896-5d57a472bc72.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/978154de-383c-49c9-a896-5d57a472bc72.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70873"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T15:17:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T15:18:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1302"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/